The '''big things''' of [[New Zealand]] are large novelty statues located in small towns which typically relate to the town and its identity.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cunningham |first=Matthew |url=http://salient.org.nz/features/small-towns-have-big-things |title=Small towns have big things |publisher=Salient |date=17 May 2010}}</ref>
Examples include: the [[Taihape]] gumboot, where gumboot-throwing is encouraged; the large [[Lemon & Paeroa|L&P]] bottle ([[Lemon]] and [[Paeroa]]) in the town where the drink originated, and the Big Sheep Shearer in [[Te Kuiti]], where the national [[Sheep shearing|sheep-shearing]] competitions are held.
A similar tradition [[Australia's big things|is found in Australia]].<ref>{{cite web | first1=Jock | last1=Phillips | url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/interactive/19431/country-town-icons | title=Country towns - New developments, 1990 onward | publisher=[[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand]] | date=14 November 2012 | accessdate=31 January 2015 | authorlink=Jock Phillips}}</ref>
