{{Infobox ancient site | name = Mata Menge | native_name = | native_name_lang = | alternate_name = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | map = | map_type = Indonesia | map_alt = | map_caption = | map_size = | relief = yes | coordinates = {{coord|8|41|31|S|121|05|43|E|display=inline,title}} | map_dot_label = | location = [[Flores]], Indonesia | region = So'a Basin | type = open-air site | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | volume = | diameter = | circumference = | height = | builder = | material = | built = | abandoned = | epochs = early [[Middle Pleistocene]] | cultures = | dependency_of = | occupants = | event = | excavations = 1991-1992,{{sfn|Morwood|1997}} 1994,{{sfn|Morwood|1997}} 2004-2006,{{sfn|Brumm|2009}} 2014{{sfn|Brumm|2016}} | archaeologists = [[Theodor Verhoeven]], [[Mike Morwood]] | condition = | ownership = | management = | public_access = | other_designation = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | notes = }} '''Mata Menge''' is an early [[Middle Pleistocene]] paleoanthropological site located in the Ola Bula Formation in the So'a Basin on the island of [[Flores]], [[Indonesia]]. Lithic artefacts and hominin remains have been discovered at the site. The level of sophistication of the Mata Menge lithic artefacts is described as being 'simple'.{{sfn|Brumm|2006}}
==Excavations== In 1970, [[Theodor Verhoeven]] and Johannes Maringer were the first to associate the remains of ''[[Stegodon|Stegodon florensis]]'' with stone artefacts, linking these together as evidence of early hominin colonization of Flores, a feat that requires crossing the open sea.{{sfn|Morwood|1997}}
A 1994 excavation yielded 45 lithic elements, consisting mostly of [[basalt]] and [[chert]], with several being classified as artefacts.{{sfn|Morwood|1997}} The fossil remains of ''[[Stegodon|Stegodon florensis]]'', ''Hooijeromys nusatenggara'', crocodile and freshwater mollusk were also discovered.{{sfn|Morwood|1997}} The 1994 excavation yielded a dating of around 730,000 BP.{{sfn|Morwood|1997}}
The 2004-2006 excavation yielded the remains of 487 lithic artefacts.{{sfn|Brumm|2006}}
==Hominin fossils== In October 2014, the fossil remains of an early hominin were discovered at the site.{{sfn|van den Bergh|2016}} A mandible and six teeth were discovered.{{sfn|van den Bergh|2016}} The hominin fossils belonged to at least three distinct individuals.{{sfn|van den Bergh|2016}} The hominin fossils were dated to around 700,000 [[Before Present|BP]],{{sfn|Brumm|2016}} making the Mata Menge fossils the oldest hominin fossils yet discovered on the island of Flores.{{sfn|van den Bergh|2016}} The fossils at Mata Menge are likely to belong to hominins that resulted from the effects of [[insular dwarfism]] working on ''[[Homo erectus]]''.{{sfn|van den Bergh|2016}}
47 lithic artefacts were discovered in the layer containing the hominin fossils.{{sfn|Brumm|2016}} The remains of ''[[Stegodon|Stegodon florensis]]'', ''{{ill|Hooijeromys nusatenggara|nl}}'', [[Komodo dragon]] and crocodile were also discovered in the layer associated with the hominin fossil remains.{{sfn|Brumm|2016}}
===Comparisons to ''Homo floresiensis''=== Hominin fossils at Mata Menge, in particular the mandible, are smaller than those of ''[[Homo floresiensis]]''.{{sfn|van den Bergh|2016}} The size and shape of the teeth of the Mata Menge fossils are similar to those of ''H. floresiensis'', but the Mata Menge fossils are more primitive.{{sfn|van den Bergh|2016}} The lithic artefacts at Mata Menge also show cultural similarities to those found at [[Liang Bua]].{{sfn|Brumm|2006}}{{sfn|van den Bergh|2016}}{{sfn|Brumm|2016}} The similarities in lithic artefacts and hominin fossil remains suggest that the hominins at Mata Menge were likely ancestral to ''H. floresiensis''.{{sfn|van den Bergh|2016}}
