{{other uses2|Serbia}} [[File:Mati Serbia i sin Serbin.jpg|200px|thumb|"Mother Serbia and son Serb", a 19th-century [[lithography]]]] '''Mother Serbia''' ({{lang-sr|Мајка Србија}} / ''Majka Srbija'', Србија мати / ''Srbija mati''; {{lang-de|Mutter Serbien}}), '''Serb Mother''' (Serbian: Српска мајка / ''Srpska majka'') or '''Mother of All Serbs'''<ref name="ŽarkovGhodsee2007">{{cite book|author1=Dubravka Žarkov|author2=Kristen Ghodsee|title=The Body of War: Media, Ethnicity, and Gender in the Break-up of Yugoslavia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lgWWg3uBBvYC&pg=PT51|date=13 August 2007|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=0-8223-9018-3|pages=51–}}</ref> (Serbian: Мајка свих Срба / ''Majka svih Srba''), is a [[national personification]] of [[Serbia]], which is the [[nation-state]] of [[Serbs]]. It was used as the metaphoric mother of all Serbs.<ref name="ŽarkovGhodsee2007"/> Serbian national myths and poems constantly invoke Mother Serbia.<ref name="Salecl2002">{{cite book|author=Renata Salecl|title=The Spoils of Freedom: Psychoanalysis, Feminism and Ideology After the Fall of Socialism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oqOJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA17|date=31 January 2002|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-90612-3|pages=17–}}</ref>
The territories inhabited by ethnic Serbs outside Serbia can be represented as the children of Mother Serbia.<ref name="Čolović2002">{{cite book|author=Ivan Čolović|title=The Politics of Symbol in Serbia: Essays in Political Anthropology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5EoJ-zjlvdoC&pg=PA32|date=January 2002|publisher=C. Hurst & Co. Publishers|isbn=978-1-85065-556-5|pages=32–33, 52}}</ref> Serbia may also be described as a daughter of Mother Serbia, alongside other Serb territories, as in Dragoslav Knežević's poem ''Mother Serbia'': "One sister younger than the older Montenegro and Serbia, In peacetime and in war Krajina joins the Serbian flock".<ref name="Čolović2002"/>
==History== [[File:Befreites Serbien.jpg|thumb|''Befreites Serbien'' ("Liberated Serbia"), depicting Mother Serbia freed from chains by the Habsburgs, [[romanticist]] work by Johann Georg Mansfeld (1763–1817) regarding [[Habsburg-occupied Serbia (1788–92)]].]] ===19th century=== [[Dositej Obradović]] (1739–1811) extensively used Mother Serbia in his works.<ref>{{cite book|author=Petar Pijanović|title=Život i delo Dositeja Obradovića: zbornik radova sa naučnog skupa Srpske akademije nauka i umetnosti održanog 15. i 16. decembra 1999. godine u Beogradu i 17. decembra 1999. godine u Sremskim Karlovcima|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FdIXAQAAIAAJ|year=2000|publisher=Zavod za udžbenike i nastavna sredstva}}</ref> The concept and term was used in many patriotic songs, such as ''[[Vostani Serbije]]'', ''[[Oj Srbijo, mila mati]]'', ''[[Oj Srbijo mati]]'', etc.
On February 24, 1874, the "Serbian Liberation Committee for the [[Sanjak of Niš]]", known simply as the ''[[Niš Committee]]'', was founded by local notables. Orthodox priest Petar Ikonomović swore [[Oath]] on the [[Christian cross]] and [[Gospel]], reminiscent of the [[Orašac Assembly]] (1804).<ref>{{cite book|author=Danica Milić|title=Istorija Niša: Od najstarijih vremena do oslobođenja od Turaka 1878. godine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oZ8MAAAAIAAJ|year=1983|publisher=Gradina|page=298}}</ref> Ikonomović said:
{{cquote|So together, brothers, and the Almighty shall help us all in his mercy, and soon permit us to weave the triumphal flag of our only faithful IV Obrenović on the [[Niš fortification]]. Hooray! Hooray! Hooray! Long live our beloved knightly Prince [[Milan M. Obrenović IV]]. Long live Mother Serbia!|author=Petar Ikonomović, priest of Niš (February 24, 1874)<ref>{{cite book|author1=Branibor Debeljković|author2=Olivera Stefanović|title=Old Serbian photography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ShchAQAAIAAJ|year=2005|publisher=Narodna biblioteka Srbije|page=165}}</ref>}}
===Inter-war period=== {{cquote|She [Serbia] sacrificed hundreds of thousands of her best sons, gave up her name, flag, existence, and eventually the blood of her king. But still they aren't satisfied and want more, they want to kill her spirit, rip out her heart, wipe out every trace of her, but this will never be! Mother Serbia will give more sacrifices, take more blows for the good of the King and our fatherland Yugoslavia, but she will endure.|author=President of the Serbian women organisation "Dobrotvorna Zadruga Srpkinja" in Sarajevo, during the inter-war period.<ref name="WingfieldBucur2006">{{cite book|author1=Nancy M. Wingfield|author2=Maria Bucur|title=Gender and War in Twentieth-Century Eastern Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FntMoF3ZNDoC&pg=PA165|date=9 May 2006|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=0-253-11193-5|pages=165–}}</ref>}}
In 1940, Pavle Tatić wrote the drama ''Srpska majka''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Pavle Tatić|title=Srpska majka: drama u tri slike sa prologom|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EHkKOwAACAAJ|year=1940|publisher=Štamparija"Natošević"}}</ref>
===World War II=== The propaganda of the Serbian puppet [[Government of National Salvation]] included promoting [[Milan Nedić]] as "Mother of the Serbs", claiming that he cared and shielded the Serbs.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Rebecca Haynes|author2=Martyn Rady|title=In the Shadow of Hitler: Personalities of the Right in Central and Eastern Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nXsqAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA302|date=30 November 2013|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-78076-808-3|pages=302–}}</ref>
===Yugoslav Wars=== The expression was used during the [[Yugoslav Wars]], referring to Mother Serbia's children in the west (outside [[Serbia and Montenegro]]) as the [[Republic of Serbian Krajina]] and [[Republika Srpska]].
[[Milan Martić]], President of the [[Republic of Serbian Krajina]] (RSK), argued, after the fall of RSK ([[Operation Storm]]), that "the people felt they had been deceived and abandoned by mother Serbia" for not protecting RSK.<ref name="Ambrosio2001">{{cite book|author=Thomas Ambrosio|title=Irredentism: Ethnic Conflict and International Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0hLzXEO-fAQC&pg=PA88|year=2001|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-97260-8|pages=88–}}</ref>
==Use in art== {{expand list|date=December 2014}} [[File:VladaSrbije.jpg|thumb|Statue of Mother Serbia at the top of the building of the [[Government of Serbia]].]] ;Statues and sculptures *A statue at the top of the building of the [[Government of Serbia]], of Mother Serbia holding a shield with the [[Serbian cross]]. *[[Milić od Mačve]]'s only sculpture, "Mother Greece and Mother Serbia" (Мајка Грчка и Мајка Србија), was erected in [[Kruševac]] in 1999, as a symbol of [[Greece–Serbia relations#NATO bombing of FR Yugoslavia|Greece's support of Serbia]] during the [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{cite book|title=NIN. nedeljne informativne novine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3tgTAQAAMAAJ|year=1999|publisher=Politika.|page=33}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sele Majku Grcku i Majku Srbiju|publisher=Politika|url=http://www.politika.rs/rubrike/Srbija/Sele-Majku-Grcku-i-Majku-Srbiju.sr.html}}</ref> *[[Đorđe Jovanović]], "Velika Srbija" (Great Serbia, 1924)
;Songs *"[[Oj Srbijo mati]]" (Oh Serbia Our Mother) *"[[Oj Srbijo, mila mati]]" (Oh Serbia, Our Gracious Mother)
